<TITLE> GP-Banglalink sign agreement to save land </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, Feb 9 (bdnenews24.com)- Grameenphone and Banglalink, two major mobile operators, have signed an agreement on sharing their infrastructure aimed minimising use of land and saving cost. The deal, 'Infrastructure Sharing Agreement' signed on Feb 1, was made public at a press conference in Hotel Sonargaon on Tuesday. Oddvar Hesjedal, chief executive officer of Grameenphone, said they had not yet decided on the amount of sharing. He also said that it had made a similar deal with AKTEL. BTRC chairman Zia Ahmed, who was present in the press conference, said GP and Banglalink had signed the deal in line with the regulatory commission's directives. Elaborating on the puspose of the agreement Ahmed said if the mobile operators provide network from the similar tower it will save land. Currently six mobile companies are operating in Bangladesh. b
